<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="549" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1142,1527]" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1214,1239]" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from other congeners by its comparatively large size (1.8−2.0 in total length); pale castaneous, sometimes yellowish brown general coloration; long, rather thick antenna; broad pronotum with a uniformly shiny, thick callus (
<figureCitation box="[492,632,1286,1311]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 − 13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1769,1792]" captionTargetBox="[185,1415,191,1723]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1435,177,1749]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 − 13. Bilia burma (8 − 11) and B. castanea (12 − 13), head and pronotum in dorsal view (8 − 10, 12 − 13) and whole body in left lateral view (11). 8, Holotype male (AMNH _ PBI 00380431). 9, Paratype male (00380432). 10 − 11, 13, Female. 12, Male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258307/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">Figs. 12−13</figureCitation>
); and longer hooked process on paramere (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1210,1286,1311]" captionStart="FIGURES 24 − 28" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1661,1684]" captionTargetBox="[173,1423,212,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1437,193,1640]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 24 − 28. Male (24 − 25, 27 − 28) and female (26) genitalia of Bilia castanea (24), B. burma n. sp. (25 − 26), B. pilosa Yasunaga (from Japan) (27), and Wollastoniella rotunda (28), named on the figures." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258310/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). Further diagnostic characters and detailed redescription, including male and female genitalia, were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carayon" pageId="5" pageNumber="549" refString="Carayon, J. &amp; Miyamoto, S. (1960) Especes nouvelles ou peu connues du genre Bilia Distant trouvees au Japon et a Formose (Heteroptera, Anthocoridae). Mushi, 33 (4), 19 - 35, tabs. 4 - 5." type="journal article" year="1960">Carayon &amp; Miyamoto (1960)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="549" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1142,1527]" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1394,1419]" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is known to feed on aphids on black mustard in 
<collectingCountry box="[999,1057,1394,1419]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">India</collectingCountry>
as mentioned above (
<bibRefCitation author="Ghosh" pageId="5" pageNumber="549" refString="Ghosh, D., Poddar, S. &amp; Raychaudhuri, D. N. (1981) Natural enemy complex of Aphis craccivora Koch and Lipaphis erysimi (Kalt.) in and around Calcutta, West Bengal. Science and Culture, 47 (2), 58 - 60." type="journal article" year="1981">
Ghosh 
<emphasis box="[1380,1436,1394,1419]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">et al.</emphasis>
1981
</bibRefCitation>
). Several specimens were collected from 
<emphasis box="[676,943,1430,1455]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="549">Nyctanthes arbor-tristis</emphasis>
L. (Oleaceae) with undetermined mites.
</paragraph>
